Linear_regression

Matthew Chen, Jasper Tsai, Mark Faynboym

2022-12-04

  • No interaction
    • model1: Linear model with all first order terms
    • model1_sqrt: Refit model1 using a square root transform in Y
    • mordel1_sqrt_aic: AIC of model1_sqrt
  • Interaction
    • model2: inclusion of all two-way interaction terms
    • model2_sqrt: Refit model2 using a square root transform in Y
    • model2_sqrt_aic: AIC of model2_sqrt
  • Analysis of Outliers
    • Bonferroni Outlier test (Outliers in Y)
    • Leverage (Outliers in X)
    • Remove outliers identified that are influential
    • model2_sqrt_aic_out: Directly refit model2_sqrt_aic onto data without outliers
    • model3: refit model2_sqrt without outliers this time
    • model3_aic: AIC of model3
    • Confidence Interval for model3_aic

In the model diagnostics, we find that residuals have no pattern, are centered about zero, and have no sign of heteroskedasticity. In the normal-QQ plot, we find that there are heavy right tails, though this may be caused by outliers in Y (we will examine these later). Overall, this model is reasonable.

Exploration of transformation in Y with original full data with model1

Since we have heavy tails in the residual distribution, we conduct the box-cox procedure to see if a transformation of the response variable would be beneficial.

The Box-Cox suggests a square root transformation of the data
we will continue to use SQRT(Y) data for rest of this section

In the QQ plot we see that the distribution is much less heavy tailed than before, and R2 and R2a also remain mostly unchanged. Thus, these tails may be caused by a handful of outliers in Y. We continue using the square root transformation of our response variable.

In the model diagnostics, we find that residuals have no pattern, are centered about zero, and have no sign of heteroskedasticity. Exploration of transformation in Y with original full data with model2

Since we have tails in the residual distribution, we conduct the box-cox procedure to see if a transformation of the response variable would be beneficial.

The Box-Cox suggests a square root transformation of the data we will continue to use SQRT(Y) data for rest of this section
